23
00:02:22,388 --> 00:02:26,191
In early 2013, we formed a team of 10 developers

24
00:02:26,651 --> 00:02:28,713
with the goal of creating a new type of game

25
00:02:28,733 --> 00:02:31,616
that wouldn't fit easily into pre-existing categories.

26
00:02:32,396 --> 00:02:34,198
We discussed our ideas together every day,

27
00:02:34,338 --> 00:02:36,339
until after half a year, we found ourselves

28
00:02:36,359 --> 00:02:38,341
with over 70 different design proposals and a number

29
00:02:38,421 --> 00:02:39,522
of software prototypes.

30
00:02:52,152 --> 00:02:55,255
The idea that formed the basis for Splatoon emerged from this process.

31
00:03:15,510 --> 00:03:17,671
Our initial prototype was fairly simplistic.

32
00:03:18,131 --> 00:03:20,952
You would move a cube-shaped character around a flat map,

33
00:03:21,413 --> 00:03:22,953
shooting out white or black ink.

34
00:03:23,914 --> 00:03:26,234
We used cubes because they were easy to create,

35
00:03:26,515 --> 00:03:29,076
and eventually ended up calling them blocks of tofu.

36
00:03:30,736 --> 00:03:36,298
At this point, we were able to connect multiple Wii Us

37
00:03:36,358 --> 00:03:38,879
and play Splatoon, where you would play as a team

38
00:03:38,899 --> 00:03:40,960
and decide who won by the area of the ground you painted.

39
00:03:41,180 --> 00:03:42,601
Of course you could also attack your opponent and beat them.

40
00:03:43,834 --> 00:03:48,876
Linking together multiple Wii U consoles allowed us to have team battles in which we'd compete

41
00:03:48,916 --> 00:03:54,139
to cover the most area with our own team's ink, and that became the core of Splatoon's

42
00:03:54,159 --> 00:03:54,659
gameplay.

43
00:03:55,379 --> 00:03:57,721
Of course, you can also attack and defeat your opponents.

44
00:04:01,882 --> 00:04:05,604
And at this stage, we'd also come up with ways to make use of the Wii U GamePad.

45
00:04:11,715 --> 00:04:16,218
Winning meant needing to ink the ground around you, but also that this would reveal your location to your opponents.

46
00:04:16,238 --> 00:04:20,601
This put players in a bit of a catch-22, and we soon realized it would be one of the most interesting and game-like aspects of our prototype.

47
00:04:45,563 --> 00:04:53,088
You might have seen it in this video, but the idea of hiding within your own ink as a way of concealing your position also emerged around this time.

48
00:04:53,108 --> 00:05:02,053
We used the feature of the Wii U, the gyro function, to create a skeleton of play while searching for a playable expression and operation.

49
00:05:05,428 --> 00:05:10,450
From there, we explored ways to leverage the Wii U's unique features like motion control

50
00:05:10,990 --> 00:05:14,151
to come up with actions and inputs that felt good to perform,

51
00:05:14,731 --> 00:05:17,272
and in so doing, build out the gameplay of our idea.

52
00:05:17,292 --> 00:05:22,434
I think that a finished game is classified as a shooter,

53
00:05:22,494 --> 00:05:24,854
and there are parts that use the word shooter.

54
00:05:24,874 --> 00:05:27,595
But we didn't try to make a shooter from the start.

55
00:05:27,615 --> 00:05:30,796
We used a technique that makes it look like a Nintendo-like action game.

56
00:05:34,318 --> 00:05:37,320
the finished game would likely fall into the shooter category.

57
00:05:37,961 --> 00:05:40,583
And parts of it make use of the language of shooters,

58
00:05:40,723 --> 00:05:44,926
but this isn't to say that we'd set out to create a shooting game from the start.

59
00:05:45,607 --> 00:05:49,590
Rather that the gameplay took this shape as a result of the methods we used

60
00:05:49,710 --> 00:05:51,892
to make a Nintendo-style action game.

61
00:05:53,153 --> 00:05:56,876
The team's ultimate goal was to create a new game,

62
00:05:56,996 --> 00:06:00,519
but our initial goal was to create a new gaming experience.

63
00:06:01,804 --> 00:06:04,365
While our end goal was to create a new game,

64
00:06:04,905 --> 00:06:07,626
the first target we aimed for was creating a new type

65
00:06:07,706 --> 00:06:08,686
of play experience.

66
00:06:11,327 --> 00:06:14,208
We believe that the appearance of a game is important,

67
00:06:14,248 --> 00:06:17,609
but we also believe that it is also important to make it

68
00:06:17,649 --> 00:06:18,850
more appealing to the player.

69
00:06:18,930 --> 00:06:23,151
Art does not have to represent the function and purpose of a game.

70
00:06:25,628 --> 00:06:27,689
So the look of a game is certainly important,

71
00:06:28,349 --> 00:06:29,710
but I think of it as something that

72
00:06:29,750 --> 00:06:32,710
makes gameplay more compelling and amplifies its appeal.

73
00:06:33,451 --> 00:06:36,471
A game's aesthetic and art must embody and complement

74
00:06:36,552 --> 00:06:37,992
its functionality and purpose.

75
00:06:40,113 --> 00:06:41,813
There were options to use existing IPs,

76
00:06:41,973 --> 00:06:44,394
but I felt that a new world and new characters

77
00:06:44,434 --> 00:06:46,994
were necessary to embody new gameplay.

78
00:06:51,282 --> 00:06:54,084
We did consider the option of using existing IP,

79
00:06:54,644 --> 00:06:57,026
but felt that new characters and a new world

80
00:06:57,146 --> 00:07:00,149
would be the best embodiment of this new play experience.

81
00:07:02,991 --> 00:07:05,353
By the way, Nintendo always has a tendency to create new things.

82
00:07:05,393 --> 00:07:07,234
That's why ARMS and Nintendo Labo were born.

83
00:07:12,797 --> 00:07:17,878
I should mention that there's a sort of ever-present desire at Nintendo to produce new things.

84
00:07:18,659 --> 00:07:23,920
Projects such as ARMS and Nintendo Labo are examples of things born out of this atmosphere.

85
00:07:23,940 --> 00:07:28,741
We don't abandon this desire to try new things even when working on established franchises,

86
00:07:28,761 --> 00:07:30,461
for example, with The Legend of Zelda Breath of the Wild.

87
00:07:41,065 --> 00:07:43,667
And on that note, I hope you'll look forward to my colleague, Mr. Yabuki's arms session,

88
